                        <div id="content" class="hfeed">
                            <article class="post-158379 post type-post status-publish hentry category-private-lives tag-breast-cancer tag-cancer tag-death-and-dying tag-friendship tag-mastectomy tag-support-groups tag-therapy-and-rehabilitation des-breast-cancer des-cancer des-death-and-dying des-friendship des-mastectomy des-therapy-and-rehabilitation nyt_request_keyword-support-groups news_keywords-breast-cancer news_keywords-cancer news_keywords-death news_keywords-friendship news_keywords-mastectomy news_keywords-therapy"
                                id="post-158379">
                                <header class="postHeader">
                                    <div class="postKicker">
                                        <span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/?module=BlogCategory&amp;version=Blog Post&amp;action=Click&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Header">Private Lives</a></span>
                                    </div>
                                    <h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">A Sisterhood of Memories</h1>
                                    <div class="story-meta-footer">
                                        <address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By RUTH PENNEBAKER			</address>
                                        <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-10-29T07:45:16+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">October 29, 2015 3:45 am</time>
                                        <!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">October 29, 2015 3:45 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
                                    </div>
                                </header>
                                <div class="entry-content">
                                    <div class="inlineModule">
                                        <div class="entry">
                                            <div class="thumb"><img alt="Private Lives" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/firstperson/firstperson45.png" width="50" height="50"></div>
                                            <p class="summary"> <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/">Private Lives:</a> Personal essays on the news of the world and the news of our lives.
                                            </p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I know the accepted wisdom: Making new friends takes longer as you age. After all, you&#x2019;re busier, more set in your ways, less open to novelty.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But nobody ever told breast cancer support groups about that crisp little sentiment. Show up at a support group when you have a fresh mastectomy scar or radiation burns, and you can find yourself enveloped in a warm
                                        emotional bath. Minutes later, you might be weeping with total strangers who are now your best friends, railing about your husband and ingrate children, blurting out your deepest terrors of metastasis and death.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If it gets too hot, someone might yank off her wig and display a scalp as white as Cream of Wheat. Someone else might remove her blouse to show off a new pi&#xE8;ce de r&#xE9;sistance of breast reconstruction.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Or maybe those were just the cancer support groups I went to in Dallas and Austin in the years following my diagnosis of Stage 2b breast cancer in September 1995. The point is, those groups saved my life and sanity.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-158379"></span></p>
                                    <div class="w480">
                                        <figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/29/opinion/29PRIVATE/29PRIVATE-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
                                            <div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/29/opinion/29PRIVATE/29PRIVATE-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/29/opinion/29PRIVATE/29PRIVATE-blog480.jpg" id="100000004004736"
                                                    width="480" height="650" alt="">
                                                <meta itemprop="height" content="650">
                                                <meta itemprop="width" content="480">
                                            </div>
                                            <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Cynthia Kittler</span>
                                            </figcaption>
                                        </figure>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I&#x2019;d spent months in surgery for a bilateral mastectomy, then chemotherapy and radiation, buoyed by family and friends and a constant supply of dinner casseroles and too much advice. I&#x2019;d been told I was
                                        brave, even though I knew I wasn&#x2019;t, and I hadn&#x2019;t bought my own lunch in months, since nobody is insensitive enough to make a cancer patient pay for her own meals.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But then, in the summer of 1996, my treatments were over, my port-a-cath had been removed, and my hair was inching back. The crisis had passed, the rest of the world was moving on, and I was supposed to &#x2014; well,
                                        <em>what</em>?</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Live your life as fully as you can,&#x201D; my oncologist said briskly. &#x201C;Do whatever you feel like doing.&#x201D; She smiled encouragingly. She also looked a little exasperated. After all, she had other
                                        patients with more pressing needs.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">She looked at me &#x2013; <em>everybody</em> looked at me &#x2013; like I was an intact person, the woman I used to be. I was furious at every one of them.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">They thought I should be happy! They told me I should feel lucky to be alive! They had no idea how damaged and crazy and isolated I felt. Night and day, fear swamped me relentlessly, leaving me shaky and weak and sick
                                        to my stomach. I flinched at every little pain, every cough; my body had already turned on me once and nothing would ever be innocuous again. How happy and lucky did that sound?</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I knew the odds. According to the cancer literature, my chances of surviving 10 years and seeing my children grow up were less than 50 percent. I wasn&#x2019;t waiting for the other shoe to drop, I was waiting for the
                                        whole damned shoe store to collapse.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So, that was the precarious mental state I was in when I began to frequent support groups. I was a mess, I was volatile, and nobody but other cancer survivors could understand me. I went to groups at the hospital where
                                        my oncologists practiced and sought out other groups. I befriended everybody I knew with a bad pathology report. When we moved from Dallas to Austin a year later, one of the first things I did was to find a new
                                        support group.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Four or five or even 20 of us in a gathering, we swapped stories, laughed hysterically, cried, embraced, gathered for marches. Sometimes, I would look around and marvel at how broken we were individually but how strong
                                        and fierce we were together. I made some of the closest friendships I&#x2019;d ever had, friendships that skipped over the usual, banal niceties and plunged into tales of liver biopsies and infected chemo ports
                                        and insensitive doctors and husbands who didn&#x2019;t understand. We raged and wept and drank wine.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But, again: Together, we felt so strong. Invincible, almost. We could handle anything, couldn&#x2019;t we?</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">No, we couldn&#x2019;t. As the months, then years began to pass, coughs lingered, shadows flickered on screens, drugs started to fail. My dear friend Martha, who had inflammatory breast cancer, sailed through repeated
                                        chemo, then gamma-knife surgery for brain lesions. Her hair fell out, it grew back, she dyed it a brassy blond. But the cancer grew back, too, again and again. One day at lunch, Martha and I sat across from each
                                        other and I asked her about her life while I took notes. We both knew I was writing her obituary.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Across town, another friend, Clare, leaned over and broke two ribs. Her cancer had metastasized to her bones. My friend Donna in Dallas had desperately tried to live to see her three children grow up. She died a day
                                        after her oldest child came to the hospital so she could see him in his high school graduation gown.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">With recurring illness, then death, groups broke up and re-formed and fractured again. Together, we&#x2019;d seemed strong and we&#x2019;d thought we had everything in common &#x2014; but our fates were individual.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Time also changed our perspectives. Fresh out of treatment, I&#x2019;d defined myself primarily as a breast cancer survivor. As the years passed and I stayed healthy, though, that identity wasn&#x2019;t as immediate.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At the 10<sup>th</sup> anniversary of my diagnosis, I was blindsided by grief. I finally understood how guilty I felt for surviving when so many of my wonderful, valiant friends had not. They had done everything they
                                        could to live, but it hadn&#x2019;t mattered; their cancers were voracious.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Sure, I&#x2019;d had support from family and friends, good health insurance, and good medical treatment but I&#x2019;d also had luck &#x2014; sheer, dumb, unwarranted luck &#x2014; and many of my friends had not. &#x201C;Deserve&#x2019;s
                                        got nothing to do with it,&#x201D; a character in my favorite Western said about who lived and who died. He was right.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Isn&#x2019;t it a shame you can&#x2019;t just be grateful for your survival &#x2013; and not feel guilty about it?&#x201D; a friend &#x2013; not a cancer survivor, of course &#x2013; said.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;And isn&#x2019;t it a shame the rest of the world can&#x2019;t shut the hell up and stop telling cancer survivors what they should feel and do?&#x201D; I wondered silently. Why say it out loud, though? Why bother?
                                        She would have never understood how intricate and ambivalent a long-term survivor&#x2019;s gratitude could be.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Now, almost 20 years past my diagnosis, I no longer think or worry about cancer every day. I live the life of a healthy, 65-year-old woman &#x2013; working, traveling, enjoying my husband and two grown children and
                                        our friends. Someone slipped up and gave me an unexpected 20 more years of life, and I&#x2019;d like to say I&#x2019;m thankful every second of every day, but I&#x2019;m human, I&#x2019;m fallible, I forget. Still,
                                        I&#x2019;ll never walk past a younger woman with telltale chemo curl growing in without telling her I understand, I&#x2019;ve been there, I wish her the same great good fortune I&#x2019;ve had.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;I&#x2019;d be so <em>proud</em> to grow old,&#x201D; my friend Martha once said. But she never made it out of her 40s.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I think of Martha and Donna and Katherine and Clare and Kathleen and Cindy and Alice and too many others as I age. I see their faces, still young and unlined. I try to remind myself how fortunate I am to be growing
                                        older, and I sometimes think I&#x2019;m trying to age well for all of us, trying to be a bigger, better, more generous person than I really am so I can honor them somehow. More than anything, I want them to know
                                        I&#x2019;ll never forget them.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So, I talk to them now and then. <em>You do slow down some as you age</em>, I tell them, <em>and your teeth hurt and everything starts to sag a little more. But it&#x2019;s a calmer, more contented time of life, lovely in unexpected ways.</em></p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>And, hey &#x2013; did I tell you? I became a grandmother in August! Yes, I have a granddaughter! Who would have thought I could make it that far? I mean, how incredibly lucky could I get?</em></p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Over those long, hard years with my friends who didn&#x2019;t make it, we always were pulling for one another to break free and live again. I think, I hope, I simply have to believe, they&#x2019;d all be happy for me.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><a href="//www.ruthpennebaker.com/biography.htm">Ruth Pennebaker</a> is a co-author of <a href="//www.amazon.com/Pucker-Up-Subversive-Perspective-Occasional/dp/0986230707/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1440769832&amp;sr=8-1&amp;keywords=BOOK+PENNEBAKER">&#x201C;Pucker Up,</a>&#x201D; a book on aging well.</em></p>
                                </div>
                                <footer class="entry-footer">
                                    <button class="button comments-button theme-speech-bubble"></button>
